1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 5. Be3 Qc7 6. Nc3 a6 7. Bd3 Nf6 8.
O-O Nxd4 9. Bxd4 Bc5 10. Bxc5 Qxc5 {In this game, we shall deal with all the
less popular moves for White. However, having a firm grasp of how to meet them
will help you to develop a feel for such positions.} 11. Qd2 $5 {This move has
subtle ideas, the main one being Rae1-e3-g3 - threatening Rg7 and other
tactical dangers. Black must play carefully.} (11. Qf3 {Intends to transfer
the queen to g3.} d6 {(preparing e5)} 12. Qg3 (12. Rad1 e5 13. Nd5 Nxd5 14.
exd5 O-O 15. c4 f5 $11) 12... O-O 13. Rfe1 e5 $11 {Black's going to play Be6
and has a very fine position.}) (11. Qe1 {The queen from this position not
only looks at ideas like Kh1-Qe1-h4, which we have already seen before, but
also Na4 followed by Qa5.} d6 12. Na4 Qd4 $1 {(attacking White's a4-knight,
and potentially b2-pawn)} (12... Qc7 {This passive move allows White to
execute his idea of clamping down on dark squares.} 13. Qe3 Bd7 (13... b5 14.
Nb6 Rb8 15. Nxc8 Rxc8 16. a4 $36) 14. Nb6 Rd8 15. a4 O-O 16. a5 $13) 13. Qa5
Bd7 14. Nb6 Rd8 15. Rad1 Bc6 16. c3 Qc5 17. Qxc5 dxc5 18. f3 Nd7 19. Nxd7 Rxd7
20. Bc2 e5 $11 {With precise moves, Black was easily able to hold the balance.}
) (11. a4 {The idea is to clamp down on the dark squares with a5. But it's too
slow and Black can catch up in the development.} d6 12. a5 Bd7 (12... e5 {Is
the usual move, but White wasn't threatening f4 or anything of that sort. So
rather than wasting time, it would make more sense to develop pieces.}) 13. Qd2
(13. Na4 $2 Qxa5 $17) 13... Bc6 $1 {Black has excellent minor pieces. All that
is left now is to 0-0.} 14. Na4 Qh5 15. Nb6 Rd8 16. Rae1 O-O {Black is totally
fine in this position.} 17. f3 (17. Re3 h6 18. f3 Qg5 {(pinning the rook, and
preparing Nh5-f4)}) 17... Qc5+ 18. Kh1 d5 $1 19. e5 Nd7 20. Nxd7 Rxd7 21. b4
Qe7 22. c3 Rc8 $11 {Black will play Rdc7, Bb5, g6 with a strong position.}) (
11. Re1 d6 12. Qd2 O-O 13. Rad1 e5 (13... Bd7 14. Bf1 Qb6 15. b3 Rac8) 14. Re3
{Converts to Qd2.}) 11... O-O (11... d6 $6 {Forces an endgame in which White
can pressurise Black.} 12. Rfd1 O-O 13. Be2 $1 {Using the same ideas that we
will see are used by White in the 11.Be2 lines.} Rd8 14. Qd4 Qxd4 15. Rxd4 e5
16. Rb4 d5 17. Nxd5 Nxd5 18. exd5 Rxd5 19. c4 Rd2 20. Rd1 Rxd1+ 21. Bxd1 $14)
12. Rae1 d6 13. Re3 (13. Kh1 {Is another possibility - looking to play f4.} e5
$1 {In a way, reducing the effect of f4.} 14. f4 Be6 15. f5 Bd7 $1 {After f5,
the bishop is always well placed on c6.} 16. Rf3 (16. g4 $6 {This primitive
attack can hardly be successful.} Bc6 {Intending d5.} 17. g5 Nh5 18. f6 g6 19.
Be2 Nf4 $40) 16... Kh8 $1 {A really key defensive move, and one that must be
understood well. The point is that h7 is well defended by Nf6 and also h6 can
be played at any time. The real weakness in Black's camp is g7, and hence this
move Kh8 makes way for the rook to come to g8 and defend that square.} 17. Qg5
(17. Nd5 Nxd5 18. exd5 f6 19. Be4 a5 $11) (17. Rg3 Rg8 $13) 17... Bc6 18. Rg3
Rg8 19. Rh3 Qb4 20. a3 Qxb2 21. Bc4 Raf8 $15 {Black is well placed!} (21...
Qxc2 $4 22. Re2 {1-0 Kotronias,V (2585)-Skripchenko,A (2459).})) 13... b5 (
13... Bd7 $146 {I always prefer development of pieces before pawn moves. Black
must understand that b5 is a luxurious move which overextends his position.
While's Bd7-c6 is a solid idea. I would always prefer the latter.} 14. Rg3 (14.
e5 $5 {Is very interesting, but with accurate play Black is able to defend. If
one wants to avoid this, one can always go for... b5 instead of Bd7N.} dxe5 15.
Rg3 g6 (15... Kh8 16. Qg5 Rg8 17. Rh3 $18) 16. Qg5 Ne8 {(preparing Ng7)} (16...
Nd5 17. Ne4 Qc7 $4 18. Qh6 f6 19. Rxg6+ hxg6 20. Qxg6+ Kh8 21. Qh6+ Kg8 22. Ng5
$18) 17. Ne4 (17. h4 Qb4 {(with an idea Qf4)} 18. Qxe5 Qxh4 19. Be4 Bc6 20.
Bxc6 bxc6 21. Rh3 Qe7 $11) 17... Qc7 18. Qh6 {(threatening Ng5)} (18. Qh4 f6 $1
