Black is going to play Bc8, b5 etc.}) 18... f6 19. Rh3 Bb5 20. c4 Bc6 $15)
14... Kh8 $1 {As previously mentioned in the notes to the last move, Kh8 is an
excellent defensive move.} (14... g6 15. Qh6 Bc6 16. Rh3 $40) 15. Rd1 (15. e5
$2 Qxe5 16. Re1 (16. Rg5 Qd4 {And now there is no Bh7 discovered check, as the
king has already moved to h8.}) 16... Qa5 $15) (15. b4 Qd4 (15... Qxb4 16. Rxg7
Kxg7 17. Qg5+ Kh8 18. Qxf6+ Kg8 19. Qg5+ Kh8 20. Qf6+ $11) 16. Ne2 Qb2 $13)
15... Bc6 16. a3 Rfd8 17. Rh3 Rac8 $11 {And Black has a very comfortable
position and can plan according to White's reactions.}) 14. Rg3 Bb7 $4 (14...
g6 {Was necessary to quell White's attack.} 15. a3 Bb7 16. Qh6 (16. Rg5 Qd4 $11
) 16... Rac8 17. Rh3 Rfe8 18. Kh1 b4 19. axb4 Qxb4 20. Nd1 $13) (14... Kh8 $6 {
Which is the usual way to defend in such positions - is not so good, because
White has a pretty response here...} 15. e5 $1 {Works because...} Qxe5 16. Re1
{And Qa5 is not possible here.} Qc5 (16... Qh5 17. Rh3 Qg4 18. Re4 $3 Nxe4 19.
Bxe4 d5 20. Rxh7+ Kg8 21. f3 $16) 17. Ne4 $14 Nxe4 18. Bxe4 Ra7 19. b4 $16 {
With Qg5 coming up, Black has a huge initiative in this position.}) 15. e5 $3 {
A very strong move which does two things: firstly, opens the bishop on d3; and
secondly, interferes with the queen's actions on the fifth rank.} dxe5 (15...
Qxe5 16. Rg5 Qd4 17. Bxh7+ $18) 16. Rxg7+ $1 {The end is swift and brutal!}
Kxg7 17. Qg5+ Kh8 18. Qxf6+ Kg8 19. Re1 {What we have learnt from this game is
that the position is extremely sharp. Black must be careful. He must know the
basic attacking ideas for White and also the common defensive ideas. Once you
know that White can fire a shot like e5! and that Black has defensive ideas
like Kh8, black can be confident and will never fall to such miniatures as in
this game.} 1-0

