1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 (4... a6 5. Nc3 Qc7 6. Bd3 Nc6 7. Be3
Nf6 8. O-O Nxd4 9. Bxd4 Bc5 {Is the Paulsen move order to reach this position.}
) 5. Nc3 Qc7 6. Be3 a6 7. Bd3 Nf6 8. O-O Nxd4 9. Bxd4 Bc5 10. Be2 $5 {At first
sight, this move looks quite toothless. In fact, Black might think: how can
White claim an advantage if he moves his same piece twice in the opening - and
it moving backwards, too? But then one starts to realise that after the
exchange of dark-squared bishops, White actually wants the 'd' file cleared,
so that he can make use of the d6 weakness. That's when we truly start to take
the move Be2 seriously. 'Generally aiming for a strategically better endgame'.}
e5 $1 {Forcing the issue for White.} (10... d6 {Gives a good endgame for White.
Black is totally under pressure and it's not easy to make accurate moves when
he is already suffocating.} 11. Bxc5 Qxc5 12. Qd3 O-O 13. Rfd1 Rd8 14. Qd4 Qxd4
15. Rxd4 e5 16. Rb4 d5 17. exd5 Nxd5 18. Nxd5 Rxd5 19. c4 Rd2 (19... Rd8 20. c5
$16) 20. Rd1 Rxd1+ 21. Bxd1 $14 {Is exactly what White is looking for by
playing 10.Be2: a safe endgame plus..}) 11. Bxc5 (11. Be3 $5 Bxe3 12. fxe3 Qc6
$1 {(This protects Black's f6-knight, preventing White's eventual Rf6
sacrifice.)} (12... d6 $2 13. Rxf6 $1 gxf6 14. Nd5 $44) 13. Qd2 O-O 14. Nd5
Nxd5 15. exd5 Qd6 $1 $11 {following with b6, Bb7, Rac8}) 11... Qxc5 {What we
have here is a clear case of advantage for black in a longer-term sense. He
has the e5 pawn fixed in such a way to White's e4 that it makes the e2 bishop
into a bad piece. But putting aside the long term for a moment, the short-term
trumps lie with White because he is way ahead in development.} 12. Qd3 (12. Qd2
{This position is different from the positions in which the White queen was on
d3. White now threatens Na4 followed by Qb4. Hence this time it's better to
play the natural and free-flowing move b5! Here are some of the analysis to
prove the point that b5 is the correct move here.} b5 (12... b6 $6 13. Rfd1 Bb7
14. Na4 Qc6 15. Qb4 $14) 13. Nd5 (13. a4 b4 14. Nd5 Nxd5 15. exd5 d6 $11) (13.
b4 $6 {This move has its strength if the queen were on d3; but Qd2 reduces its
effect, as Nc3 is pinned.} Qxb4 14. a4 Bb7 15. axb5 (15. Rfb1 Qd4 $11) 15...
axb5 16. Rxa8+ Bxa8 $11 17. Rb1 Nxe4 18. Rxb4 Nxd2 19. Rxb5 Ke7 20. Rxe5+ Kf6
$11) 13... Nxe4 14. Qd3 Bb7 15. Rad1 Bxd5 16. Qxd5 Qxd5 17. Rxd5 d6 18. f3 Nf6
19. Rxd6 Ke7 20. Rfd1 Rhd8 $11) 12... b5 $6 {This looks highly illogical to me.
Black is behind in development and makes a pawn move on the queen side which
gives a hook for White to attack. This hook further enhances White's
development lead. Hence it is important for Black to come up with a better
move in this position.} (12... b6 $1 $146 {Black has the same idea as in the
game, of developing the bishop on b7 - but doesn't expose the b5 pawn as a
hook.} 13. Qc4 (13. Rfd1 Bb7 14. a3 Rc8 15. Bf3 O-O 16. Qd6 a5 $11) (13. Nd5
Nxd5 14. exd5 O-O 15. c4 a5 16. a3 a4 $11) 13... Qxc4 14. Bxc4 d6 (14... Bb7 $6
15. f4 $1 $14) 15. Rfd1 (15. f4 Be6 $1 $11) 15... Ke7 16. Nd5+ Nxd5 17. Bxd5
Ra7 18. a4 Be6 19. c4 Rc7 $11) (12... d6 $6 13. Rad1 Ke7 14. Qg3 Kf8 15. Nd5
$16 {Is a very uncomfortable position for Black.}) 13. a4 (13. b4 Qxb4 14. a4
$44 {This should also be extremely dangerous for Black. He is way behind in
development and White has a dangerous initiative.}) 13... b4 14. Nd5 Nxd5 15.
Qxd5 Qxd5 16. exd5 d6 {Black has a playable position here.} 17. f4 f6 18. a5
Ke7 19. fxe5 fxe5 20. c3 Bb7 21. c4 Bc8 22. Rad1 Rf8 23. Rxf8 Kxf8 24. c5 dxc5
25. d6 Be6 26. Rc1 Ke8 27. Rxc5 Kd7 28. Bf3 Rf8 29. Rc7+ Kxd6 30. Rc6+ Ke7 31.
Rxa6 Bc4 32. Rb6 e4 33. Rxb4 Bd3 34. Be2 Rc8 35. Bxd3 exd3 36. Kf2 Rc5 37. a6
Re5 38. a7 d2 39. Rb7+ Ke6 40. a8=Q d1=Q 41. Qc8+ {Overall, I think the Be2
line must not be taken lightly. The important move for Black to remember is
that, instead of the overextending b5, he must play the safe move 12...b6 -
when his position will remain solid and he'll get all the benefits of the move
b5.} 1-0

